"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750000","Cabinet Office","false","2017-07-27","<p>Our priority has been to identify and test buildings clad in Aluminium Composite Material (ACM) and which, are either social or private rented housing, or public sector buildings meeting certain height thresholds.</p><p> </p><p>We are continuing to receive and analyse data on the wider public sector estate. There are range of public sector buildings currently being checked including hospitals, schools, prisons and probation facilities, care homes, military accommodation and other buildings used for overnight accommodation.</p><p> </p><p>Where screening tests indicate that ACM samples would not meet the limited combustibility requirements of the current Building Regulations guidance, the Government will inform the building owner and notify the fire and rescue service and local authority of the test result. Clear guidance has been issued to ensure the safety of buildings and occupants. Where appropriate, organisations are working with the fire and rescue service to put in place precautionary safety checks and measures.</p><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-07-27T12:52:19.627Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750000/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750000/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750000/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-07-10","Public Sector: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, with reference to his oral contribution of 26 June 2017, Official Report, column 348, if he will list the public sector buildings which are now undergoing checks.","false","Biography information for Mary Creagh","Wakefield","Mary Creagh","3903"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750001","Cabinet Office","false","2017-07-18","<p>Official residences are assigned to ministers at the discretion of the Prime Minister, either on the grounds of security or to allow them to better perform their official duties. The current allocations are as follows: the Prime Minister has No 11 Downing Street; the Chancellor has No 10 Downing Street and the Foreign Secretary has No 1 Carlton Gardens. The flats in Admiralty House are not occupied. In addition, the Prime Minister has use of Chequers, the Chancellor has use of Dorneywood; the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland has use of Hillsborough Castle and the Foreign Secretary, the Secretary of State for International Trade and the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union have joint use of Chevening.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-07-18T14:12:36.113Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750001/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750001/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750001/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-07-10","Official Residences","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, if he will provide a list of ministerial residences and their authorised occupants.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","3866"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750002","Cabinet Office","false","2017-07-18","<p>The Cabinet Office 2016-17 Annual Report and Accounts will be published in due course.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-07-18T15:11:05.233Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750002/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750002/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750002/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-07-10","Cabinet Office: Annual Reports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, when he plans to publish his Department's Annual Report and Accounts 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","3867"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750003","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-13","<p>The funding of £770 million, to which my Rt Hon Friend referred, is to be disbursed by government to the Cambridgeshire and Peterborough Combined Authority and comprises £600 million capital investment funding to be paid at £20 million per year for 30 years, and £170 million to be made available for housing and infrastructure, £70 million being for investment in Cambridge City. In addition, the Combined Authority Mayor has powers to set a precept for 2018/19 and subsequent years, with increases subject to the council tax referendum arrangements.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-07-13T16:41:53.437Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750003/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750003/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750003/answer","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750003/answer/previousversion/4334","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-10","Mayors","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to his oral contribution of 5 July 2017, Official Report, column 1156, on revenue-raising powers for mayors, who will disburse the new funding referred; how that funding will be disbursed; and whether that funding will be available to all local authorities across England.","false","Biography information for Heidi Allen","South Cambridgeshire","Heidi Allen","3826"
