"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750043","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-19","<p>Responses to the White Paper <em>Fixing Our Broken Housing Market</em> are being analysed at present. The Government intends to issue a response in due course.</p><p />","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-07-19T14:31:39.193Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750043/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750043/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750043/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-10","Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, when he plans to respond to representations received for the consultation on the housing white paper which closed on 2 May 2017.","false","Biography information for Sir Gary Streeter","South West Devon","Mr Gary Streeter","3963"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750044","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-09-11","<p>As of 10 September 2017 the Building Research Establishment had received 1523 samples to be tested under the Government’s screening programme.</p><p>All 538 samples which were Aluminium Composite Material (ACM) cladding have been tested and landlords informed of the result. The remaining samples were not ACM and therefore outside the scope of the Government’s screening programme.</p><p> </p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma","4092","2017-09-11T15:15:41.003Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750044/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750044/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750044/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-10","High Rise Flats: Fire Prevention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what number and proportion of housing cladding samples have been tested within 24 hours of receipt.","false","Biography information for Helen Hayes","Dulwich and West Norwood","Helen Hayes","4089"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750045","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-09-06","<p>In line with advice from a panel of independent experts, the testing process for cladding samples being run by the Building Research Establishment (BRE) is specifically designed to characterise the core of Aluminium Composite Material (ACM) cladding samples.</p><p>The tests are not designed for, nor can they provide suitable information on, any non-Aluminium Composite Material (ACM) cladding samples.</p><p>In each of these cases the landlord will be informed that their sample is not ACM cladding and has not been tested. All non-ACM samples are being kept by the BRE until further notice.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-09-06T16:13:51.057Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750045/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750045/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750045/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-10","High Rise Flats: Fire Prevention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, by what date all the non-ACM housing cladding samples received to date will be tested.","false","Biography information for Helen Hayes","Dulwich and West Norwood","Helen Hayes","4090"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750046","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-20","<p>The immediate priority was to identify the scale of use of Aluminium Composite Material ACM type cladding on buildings over 18 metres. On the advice of the Independent Expert panel, the Government has now commissioned the Building Research Establishment to test different wall cladding systems using three common types of ACM panelling with two commonly used types of insulation. The results will provide further evidence of how some commonly used wall systems using ACM perform in a fire. This evidence will be used to produce further advice to inform building owners’ decisions on whether they need to take any additional action to make their buildings safe.</p><p>Advice was provided on 14 July in a note to all building control bodies, which highlighted the key Building Regulation requirements when cladding work on high rise buildings over 18 metres tall is undertaken. That note can be found at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/news/ensure-that-recladding-work-meets-building-regulations-advises-expert-panel" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/news/ensure-that-recladding-work-meets-building-regulations-advises-expert-panel</a></p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-07-20T15:24:29.407Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750046/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750046/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750046/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-10","High Rise Flats: Fire Prevention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, for what reasons non-ACM housing cladding samples received by his Department have not yet been tested.","false","Biography information for Helen Hayes","Dulwich and West Norwood","Helen Hayes","4091"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750047","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-09-11","<p>As of 10 September 2017 the Building Research Establishment had received 1523 samples to be tested under the Government’s screening programme.</p><p>All 538 samples which were Aluminium Composite Material (ACM) cladding have been tested and landlords informed of the result. The remaining samples were not ACM and therefore outside the scope of the Government’s screening programme.</p><p> </p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma","4089","2017-09-11T15:15:41.067Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750047/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750047/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750047/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-10","High Rise Flats: Fire Prevention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many housing cladding samples of all types the Government has received; and how many such samples have been tested to date.","false","Biography information for Helen Hayes","Dulwich and West Norwood","Helen Hayes","4092"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750048","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-19","<p>Only three applications had been received by October 2016 which proved insufficient for a meaningful assessment to be made. The Department did not therefore carry out a formal review of the changes to selective licensing introduced from April 2015. Since then we have received a further number of applications and will soon be in a position to undertake a review. I will ensure the findings of the review are placed in the Library when it is complete.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-07-19T13:57:26.067Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750048/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750048/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750048/answer","Reading West","Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750048/answer/previousversion/4339","Biography information for Alok Sharma","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-10","Landlords","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, with reference to the contribution of Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon of 23 March 2015 to proceedings on the Selective Licensing of Houses (Additional Conditions) (England) Order 2015, Official Report, HL Deb, column 331, whether the review of the impact of those changes 18 months after their introduction has been undertaken; and if he will place a copy of that review in the Library.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","4098"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750049","Department of Health","false","2017-07-18","<p>In 2015/16 Southampton Local Authority provided short term support to 1,585 people aged over 65 and long term support to 2,605 people aged over 65.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2017-07-18T10:28:49.51Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750049/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750049/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750049/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-07-10","Social Services: Southampton","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many elderly people Southampton City Council supports with adult social care.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","4119"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750050","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-14","<p>Information on adult social care and children’s social care by all local authorities in England are published each year on the Department’s website:<br><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/local-authority-revenue-expenditure-and-financing" target="_blank">ttps://www.gov.uk/government/collections/local-authority-revenue-expenditure-and-financing</a></p><p>Information for Southampton is available in the detailed by-authority tables at the link above.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","4122","2017-07-14T17:43:41.777Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750050/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750050/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750050/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-10","Social Services: Southampton","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what the annual financial cost of adult social care was to Southampton City Council in the last seven years.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","4120"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750051","Department for Education","false","2017-07-24","<p>I am sorry, but we do not collect data on the total number of children local authorities support through children’s services departments. We do publish data on numbers of ‘children in need’ in each local authority area.</p><p> </p><p>A child in need is defined under the Children Act 1989 as “a child who is unlikely to reach or maintain a satisfactory level of health or development, or their health or development will be significantly impaired, without the provision of services, or the child is disabled.”</p><p> </p><p>The number of children in need at 31 March 2016, for Southampton City Council was 3,444.</p><p>This information is publically available in table B1 of the “Characteristics of children in Need 2016-17” main tables, which can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/characteristics-of-children-in-need-2015-to-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/characteristics-of-children-in-need-2015-to-2016</a>.</p><p><strong><br> </strong></p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-07-24T15:51:31.873Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750051/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750051/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750051/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-07-10","Social Services: Southampton","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many young people Southampton City Council supports for child services.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","4121"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750052","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-14","<p>Information on adult social care and children’s social care by all local authorities in England are published each year on the Department’s website:<br><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/local-authority-revenue-expenditure-and-financing" target="_blank">ttps://www.gov.uk/government/collections/local-authority-revenue-expenditure-and-financing</a></p><p>Information for Southampton is available in the detailed by-authority tables at the link above.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","4120","2017-07-14T17:43:41.883Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750052/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750052/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750052/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-10","Social Services: Southampton","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what the annual financial cost was to Southampton City Council of supporting child services in the last seven years.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","4122"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750053","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-14","<p>Where work is necessary to ensure the fire safety of social housing, we will ensure that lack of financial resources will not prevent it going ahead.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-07-14T11:21:00.217Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750053/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750053/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750053/answer","Reading West","Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750053/answer/previousversion/4338","Biography information for Alok Sharma","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-10","High Rise Flats: Fire Prevention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment he has made of whether additional costs to local authorities for fire prevention measures in tower blocks will reduce expenditure on the maintenance of other social housing.","false","Biography information for Mr Clive Betts","Sheffield South East","Mr Clive Betts","3909"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750054","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-14","<p>The financial settlements for South Tyneside and for Gateshead are broadly flat in cash terms between 2016-17 and 19-20. As democratically elected organisations, local authorities such as South Tyneside and Gateshead are independent of central government and are responsible for managing their budgets in line with local priorities. In 2016-17 we offered local authorities a 4-year settlement that guarantees their allocations for Revenue Support Grant, Rural Services Delivery Grant and Transition Grant, and that Business Rates top up and tariff payments will not change to reflect changes in relative needs. This offer was accepted by 97 per cent of councils including South Tyneside and Gateshead, enabling authorities to plan ahead with confidence, and meet the challenge of making savings, while continuing to provide excellent services to local communities.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-07-14T17:44:43.753Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750054/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750054/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750054/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-10","Local Government Finance: Tyne and Wear","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of changes in local authority funding on the capacity of (a) South Tyneside and (b) Gateshead local authority to deliver essential services.","false","Biography information for Mr Stephen Hepburn","Jarrow","Mr Stephen Hepburn","3935"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750055","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-19","<p>Officials and Ministers regularly meet with representatives of house building companies to discuss a wide range of issues. We are not aware of any meetings specifically to discuss the introduction of fire sprinklers.</p><p>The Department did write to all social housing providers in 2013 following the recommendations in a Coroner’s report into firefighter deaths which occurred at Shirley Towers in Southampton in April 2010. That letter encouraged providers to consider the retrofitting of sprinklers in older residential tower blocks. The Department then reinforced the content of that letter in its response to the Coroner’s report into the Lakanal House Fire – a copy of which can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/205567/Annex_B_-_SoS_DCLG_Rule_43_response.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/205567/Annex_B_-_SoS_DCLG_Rule_43_response.pdf</a></p><p> </p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-07-19T14:26:44.12Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750055/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750055/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750055/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-10","High Rise Flats: Fire Extinguishers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many meetings his Department has had with representatives of house building companies on the introduction of fire sprinklers in each year for which information is available.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","3911"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750056","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-18","<p>The Department does not collect this information.</p><p>Employment matters are for local authorities as the independent employers to decide. The Department does collect certain headline workforce data but this does not include an analysis and breakdown of job roles within the sector.</p><p> </p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-07-18T16:06:26.447Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750056/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750056/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750056/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-10","Building Regulations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many building control officers were employed in each local authority area in (a) 2010 and (b) the latest year for which information is available.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","3912"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750057","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-20","<p>The decision to retrospectively install sprinklers in Callow Towers in Sheffield in 2011 was taken by the local authority. The Department did not make an estimate of the costs.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-07-20T15:05:04.607Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750057/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750057/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750057/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-10","High Rise Flats: Sheffield","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what estimate he has made of the unit costs of retrofitting sprinkler fire protection in Callow Towers high rise flats in Sheffield.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","3913"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750058","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-18","<p>This information is not held centrally and could be provided only at disproportionate cost.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-07-18T16:05:19.747Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750058/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750058/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750058/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-10","Department for Communities and Local Government: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many contracts put out to tender by his Department have been (a) cancelled and (b) re-tendered in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","3999"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750059","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-18","<p>The information requested is not collected centrally. Local planning authorities determine planning applications and are required only to submit information to the Department on the number and nature of planning applications received and decisions made.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-07-18T16:23:31.27Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750059/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750059/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750059/answer","Reading West","Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750059/answer/previousversion/4336","Biography information for Alok Sharma","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-10","High Rise Flats: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what information his Department holds on the number of residential tower blocks which are (a) currently being built and (b) due to start construction soon.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","3904"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750060","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-20","<p>We do not intend to put a moratorium on new development of tower blocks. Where new tower blocks are being built, they must meet the requirements of the Building Regulations.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-07-20T16:45:18.203Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750060/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750060/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750060/answer","Reading West","Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750060/answer/previousversion/4337","Biography information for Alok Sharma","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-10","High Rise Flats: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will make an assessment of the potential merits of recommending a moratorium on the construction of new residential tower blocks until the recommendations of the inquiry into the Grenfell Tower fire have been published.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","3905"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750061","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-19","<p>The priority must always be ensuring the safety of residents. Where Aluminium Composite Material (ACM) cladding is present on housing over 18 metres in height, the Government is providing testing for local authorities, housing associations and private sector landlords free of charge. If the screening tests indicate that such cladding would not meet the limited combustibility requirements of the current Building Regulations guidance, local authorities, housing associations, private sector landlords and the fire and rescue service will determine the best course of action, communicating closely with residents. We have given landlords advice on the immediate mitigating actions they should take and are consulting an expert advisory panel to develop further advice. We will publish a list of buildings tested in due course.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma","1339","2017-07-19T16:25:33.51Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750061/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750061/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750061/answer","Reading West","Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750061/answer/previousversion/4335","Biography information for Alok Sharma","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-10","Government Departments: Fire Prevention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, with reference to his oral contribution of 26 June 2017, Official Report, column 348, if he will list the 15 buildings that are part of the Government estate that require further investigation.","false","Biography information for Mary Creagh","Wakefield","Mary Creagh","3902"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750062","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-18","<p>On 5 December 2016, Dame Louise Casey published her independent review of how to boost opportunity and integration in isolated and deprived communities. Since then my Department has been reviewing the available evidence on the main causes of poor integration. In the coming months we will bring forward plans for tackling these issues through a new integration strategy.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-07-18T16:07:21.207Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750062/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750062/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750062/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-10","Opportunity and Integration Review","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, when his Department plans to respond to the Casey Review into opportunity and integration.","false","Biography information for Liam Byrne","Birmingham, Hodge Hill","Liam Byrne","3859"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750063","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-13","<p>Managing waiting lists for adaptations is a matter for local authorities but government has significantly increased funding for the Disabled Facilities Grant to ensure that more people receive the adaptations they need promptly and to help local areas reduce waiting times for adaptations. Funding for 2017-18 is £431 million. This will rise to £468 million in 2018-19, and exceed £500 million in 2019-20.</p><p>Government also funds Foundations, the National Body for Home Improvement Agencies, to offer advice and support on delivery of adaptations to Home Improvement Agencies and providers of handyperson services in England. More information can be found at: <a href="http://www.foundations.uk.com/about-us/foundations/" target="_blank">http://www.foundations.uk.com/about-us/foundations/</a></p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-07-13T16:45:26.537Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750063/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750063/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750063/answer","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750063/answer/previousversion/4333","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-10","Disabled Facilities Grants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many disabled people have waited for longer than six months for adaptions to their home funded by Disability Facilities Grants in England in each of the last seven years.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","3823"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750064","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-20","<p>The Secretary of State has regular meetings to discuss housing matters, including leasehold reform. The Secretary of State made his views clear at the Home Builders Federation’s Policy Conference of 28 March 2017.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-07-20T14:58:00.35Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750064/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750064/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750064/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-10","Leasehold","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what recent meetings he has attended on leasehold reform.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","3832"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750065","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-17","<p>Local authorities are responsible for designing their own application process for discretionary housing payments and any local welfare provision scheme they run.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-07-17T16:07:29.017Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750065/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750065/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750065/answer","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750065/answer/previousversion/4331","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-10","Social Security Benefits: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will make it compulsory for a declaration of disability to feature on local authority application forms for (a) discretionary housing and (b) hardship payment.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","3820"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750066","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-07-13","<p>In England 268 Local Authorities have signed up to the Disability Confident scheme.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-07-13T09:32:48.83Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750066/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750066/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750066/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-10","Local Government: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many local authorities in England are Disability Confident.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","3821"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750067","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-13","<p>Government is committed to helping vulnerable older and disabled people to live independently and safely. In the 2015 Spending Review, Government committed to a year-on-year increase for the Disabled Facilities Grant over the five years of the Spending Review period, rising to over £500 million by 2020.</p><p>Since 2012 we have invested £1.65 billion into the Disabled Facilities Grant, providing around 250,000 adaptations. Funding has increased from £220 million in 2015-16 to £431 million in 2017-18. In 2018-19, it will rise to £468 million, and exceed £500 million in 2018-20.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-07-13T16:43:12.347Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750067/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750067/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750067/answer","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750067/answer/previousversion/4332","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-10","Disabled Facilities Grants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, whether he plans to increase funding for the Disabled Facilities Grant.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","3822"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750068","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-14","<p>In December 2016, Dame Louise Casey published her independent review of how to boost opportunity and integration in isolated and deprived communities. Since then the Department for Communities and Local Government has been reviewing the available evidence on the main causes of poor integration. In the coming months we will bring forward plans for tackling these issues through a new integration strategy.</p><p>There is currently an independent Review of Full Time Social Action by Young People, which is being led by Steve Holliday CBE. This aims to establish how many young people are engaged in full-time social action, as well as making recommendations to Government for how full-time social action can be supported in the future.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-07-14T17:45:14.683Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750068/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750068/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750068/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-10","Community Development","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, when his Department plans to publish its social integration strategy; and what assessment that strategy will make of the effect of youth full-time social action on social integration.","false","Biography information for Kate Green","Stretford and Urmston","Kate Green","3837"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750069","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-19","<p>The Government does not hold this information but is aware of this issue and is determined to act to address any abuses within the leasehold system.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-07-19T14:33:25.577Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750069/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750069/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750069/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-10","Leasehold","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what estimate he has made of the proportion of leasehold properties affected by contracts specifying the periodic doubling of ground rent.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","3834"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750070","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-19","<p>The Department’s statistics on the Help to Buy: Equity Loan scheme are published and available at the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/help-to-buy-equity-loan-scheme-and-help-to-buy-newbuy-statistics-april-2013-to-march-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/help-to-buy-equity-loan-scheme-and-help-to-buy-newbuy-statistics-april-2013-to-march-2017</a></p><p>This includes Tables 9, 9b and 9c with completions by property type and tenure (freehold and leasehold) on a cumulative, quarterly and local authority basis.</p><p> </p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-07-19T14:30:34.44Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750070/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750070/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750070/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-10","Help to Buy Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what estimate he has made of the proportion of help to buy properties which are (a) leasehold and (b) freehold.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","3833"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750071","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-19","<p>The Planning Inspectorate does not hold the information requested.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-07-19T14:28:37.383Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750071/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750071/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750071/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-10","Affordable Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many planning appeals have been made on affordable housing allocations in each of the last 10 years for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","3831"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750072","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-14","<p>The Government has not carried out an assessment on the effect of borough-wide licensing schemes on the value of buy-to-rent properties in (a) London and (b) each London borough.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-07-14T11:18:39.303Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750072/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750072/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750072/answer","Reading West","Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750072/answer/previousversion/4329","Biography information for Alok Sharma","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-10","Private Rented Housing: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment he has made of the effect of borough-wide licensing schemes on the value of buy-to-rent properties in (a) London and (b) each London borough.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","3795"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750073","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-20","<p>My officials are working with the council to understand the policy and ensure that the insurers honour their obligations. It would not be appropriate to make any further statement at this time as discussions with the insurer are on going.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-07-20T13:34:41.143Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750073/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750073/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750073/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-10","Grenfell Tower: Fires","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what estimate he has made of the adequacy of insurance cover held by Kensington and Chelsea Council to meet the costs of the consequences of the Grenfell Tower fire; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","New Forest West","Sir Desmond Swayne","3813"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750074","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-13","<p>The Department does not collect detailed information on the staff employed by local authorities. It is for individual councils to make their own decisions about how their local workforces are organised. In doing so, we expect councils to take into account their duties and responsibilities as employers under employment law and other relevant legislation.<strong><p><p><br></strong></p><p> </p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-07-13T16:45:50.67Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750074/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750074/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750074/answer","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750074/answer/previousversion/4330","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-10","Local Government: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many disabled people are employed (a) full-time and (b) part-time by local authorities in England.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","3805"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750075","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-07-13","<p>A review of gaming machines and social responsibility measures was launched in October 2016. The 31 January report by the APPG on FOBTs will be taken into consideration as part of the review.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2017-07-13T07:46:26.18Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750075/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750075/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750075/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-07-10","Gaming Machines: Reviews","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, whether she has made an assessment of the findings of the Fixed Odds Betting Terminals All Party Parliamentary Group Inquiry report, published on 31 January 2017.","false","Biography information for Patricia Gibson","North Ayrshire and Arran","Patricia Gibson","3806"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750076","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-07-17","<p>The independent Review of Full Time Social Action by Young People, which is being led by Steve Holliday CBE, aims to establish how many young people are engaged in full-time social action, as well as making recommendations to Government for how full-time social action can be supported in the future.</p><p> </p><p>The National Youth Social Action Survey showed that 42% of 10-20 year olds took part in meaningful social action during 2016.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2017-07-17T13:48:06.42Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750076/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750076/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750076/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-07-10","Voluntary Work: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, if she will take steps to record how many young people are engaged in full-time social action; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Kate Green","Stretford and Urmston","Kate Green","3838"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750077","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-07-13","<p>A review of gaming machines and social responsibility measures was launched in October 2016. Due to the cross government process required prior to publication, we do not anticipate any further announcements before October.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2017-07-13T07:33:44.837Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750077/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750077/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750077/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-07-10","Gaming Machines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, when the Review of Stakes and Prizes will be published.","false","Biography information for Patricia Gibson","North Ayrshire and Arran","Patricia Gibson","3756"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750078","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-07-13","<p>In 2012, following full public consultation on options, the Government brought into force a single classification system for video games, based on the Pan European Games Information (PEGI) age ratings. The PEGI ratings criteria are reviewed on an annual basis, and the latest moderation in 2016 ushered in a number of modifications. These are influenced by the UK Sensibilities Study, which our Games Rating Authority is required to take into account as per the Video Recordings Act. Age ratings play an important role in providing greater clarity for consumers around the age-suitability of products, and Government will continue to work with industry and the age ratings bodies to encourage their further promotion.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-07-13T15:01:19.44Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750078/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750078/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750078/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-07-10","Video Games: Classification Schemes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment she has made of the fitness for purpose of age certification for videogames.","false","Biography information for Ben Lake","Ceredigion","Ben Lake","3779"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750079","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-07-13","<p>Age restrictions are applied at the point of sale, which means that any retailer convicted of supplying a PEGI 12, 16 or 18 product to someone not meeting the specific age requirement faces a possible jail term and/or fine. Educational initiatives such as AskAboutGames are in place to encourage parents/carers to look carefully at the age ratings and content advice when making purchases for children, and Government will continue to work with industry to support adults to making responsible, informed decisions that protect children from inappropriate content.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-07-13T15:02:20.367Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750079/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750079/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750079/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-07-10","Video Games","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment she has made of the penalties for (a) parents or guardians and (b) retailers who knowingly provide videogames to children who are younger than the recommended age rating.","false","Biography information for Ben Lake","Ceredigion","Ben Lake","3780"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750080","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-07-13","<p>Ministers regularly discuss a wide range of issues with BT and Openreach.</p><p> </p><p>Openreach has introduced an online mapping tool, which provides other telecoms providers with the locations of its poles and underground ducts, although the tool was introduced in the context of PIA (its duct and pole access remedy).</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-07-13T15:19:49.443Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750080/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750080/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750080/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-07-10","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what discussions her Department has had with BT and Openreach on the location of unlit fibre and ducting laid across the UK.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kerr","Stirling","Stephen Kerr","3751"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750081","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-07-13","<p>Ministers regularly discuss a wide range of issues with BT and Openreach.</p><p>The use of utility infrastructure to deploy telecommunications fibre has been made easier by the Communications (Access to Infrastructure) Regulations 2016, which transposed the EU Broadband Cost Reduction Directive to UK law. This ensures that digital communications providers can access other providers’ physical infrastructure, across a range of sectors, on fair and reasonable terms.</p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-07-13T15:20:21.587Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750081/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750081/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750081/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-07-10","Broadband: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what discussions her Department has had with BT and Openreach on pilot projects to utilise fibre laid above ground via existing utility poles, especially in rural areas of Scotland.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kerr","Stirling","Stephen Kerr","3752"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750082","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-07-13","<p>The UK will seek to protect the ability of individuals who are eligible for a UK European Health Insurance Card (EHIC), before the specified date, to continue to benefit from free, or reduced cost, needs-arising healthcare while on a temporary stay in the EU. This is subject to the EU agreeing that these rights will be reciprocated by EU member states. The UK will also seek an ongoing arrangement akin to the EHIC scheme as part of negotiations on our future arrangements with the EU.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-07-13T15:05:16.457Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750082/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750082/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750082/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-07-10","Health Services: Reciprocal Arrangements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what recent discussions she has had with the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union on the potential benefits for UK performers touring abroad of retaining membership of the European Health Insurance Card system after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","3818"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750083","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-07-13","<p>There are no current plans to re-join Eurimages following the UK's departure in 1995. We will continue to keep under review how such programmes can support British film.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-07-13T14:58:51.433Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750083/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750083/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750083/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-07-10","Eurimages","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, whether the Government plans to re-join Eurimages.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","3819"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750084","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-07-13","<p>European organisations, who are the social partners that contribute and engage with the Sectoral Social Dialogue Committee are not restricted to organisations that are within the EU. For example, the EBU (European Broadcasting Union), which represents 73 public service broadcasters in 56 Countries, participates in the Sectoral Social Dialogue Committee for Audio-visual. Insofar as UK organisations are represented in the social partners, we expect no change to the continued participation</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-07-13T15:03:57.903Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750084/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750084/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750084/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-07-10","Arts: European Union","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what steps she is taking to ensure the UK's continued participation in the Sectoral Social Dialogue Committees on (a) live performance and (b) audio-visual after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","3824"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750085","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-07-13","<p>The Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport has held a series of roundtables with the sector on the impacts and opportunities affecting the creative industries as a result of the UK's exit from the EU, including representations from the music industry regarding the free movement of orchestras and musicians. The Department remains committed to working closely with the music sector on new arrangements after the UK leaves the EU.</p>","Salisbury","John Glen",,"2017-07-13T12:03:00.013Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750085/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750085/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750085/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-07-10","Musicians: Entry Clearances","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment she has made of the potential effect on the travelling of orchestras and orchestral performers of new visa arrangements for people entering the UK from the EU after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","3825"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750086","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-07-18","<p>Ofcom has published (April 2017) a consultation on duct and pole access (DPA - sometimes called passive infrastructure access - PIA), which proposed to make such access faster, easier and cheaper. Altnet providers, such as WarwickNet, are already using PIA to connect customers on much shorter timescales than previously.</p><p> </p><p>In the consultation, Ofcom outlined how the planning and deployment of fibre infrastructure using PIA should be improved. Openreach is already providing telecoms providers with better network information, with its PIA Digital Mapping Tool, and streamlining operational processes.</p><p> </p><p>Ofcom also proposed capping Openreach’s rental charges for PIA access and redistributing the costs of changes to the network across all users. These proposals would make it cheaper for other telecoms providers to deploy fibre using Openreach’s duct and pole infrastructure.</p><p> </p><p>Ofcom will set out more detail on these proposals later in the summer.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-07-18T10:08:28.76Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750086/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750086/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750086/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-07-10","Broadband: Small Businesses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment she has made of the (a) time taken and (b) costs paid by small businesses to access British Telecom ducts under physical infrastructure access regulations.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","3871"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750087","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-07-18","<p>Leaving the EU means we will want to take our own decisions about how to deliver the policy objectives previously targeted by EU funding. We are discussing closely with stakeholders to review all EU funding schemes in the round, to ensure that any ongoing funding commitments best serve the UK‘s national interest.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-07-18T10:06:35.037Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750087/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750087/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750087/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-07-10","Culture: EU Grants and Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, whether funding for the creative industries will remain at the same level as currently received from Creative Europe in the event that the UK ceases paying into Creative Europe when the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","3959"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750088","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-07-13","<p>Ensuring that our arts and culture represent everyone is good for business, good for creativity and good for our communities. The Secretary of State, her Ministerial team and DCMS officials reguarly meet with a wide range of stakeholders across the arts and culture sector including Arts Council England and performing arts organisations and discuss a number of issues including what can be done to support diversity both on and off the stage.</p><p> </p><p>The Arts Council has committed £11.8m of its strategic funds since December 2015 to support and increase diversity within the arts including the Sustained Theatre Fund which offers support to the development of BME theatre makers across the wider theatre sector in England. The fund has awarded £500,000 to eleven organisations including Eclipse Theatre who will deliver a programme that will support over 1,200 black artists in the North by increasing access to local, national and international networks and opportunities for BAME artists.</p>","Salisbury","John Glen",,"2017-07-13T12:00:01.137Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750088/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750088/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750088/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-07-10","Performing Arts: Equality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what recent discussions she has had with representatives of the performing arts industry on diversity and social mobility of performers in that industry.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","4051"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750089","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-07-17","<p>Government is committed to building the resilience and independence of smaller charities. Through our ongoing dialogue with representatives from across the sector, we know that small charities can struggle to raise the resources they need.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>In recognition of this, the Office for Civil Society in England are providing a multi-year programme of fundraising training and support. In addition to face-to-face training, intensive one-to-one advice sessions and webinars, the programme includes skilled volunteer mentoring, connecting small charities with experienced fundraisers to provide longer term support. The training and support will be provided at little or no cost and the providers will also develop and share fundraising training resources and toolkits to support small charities who might not be able to attend training.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>Our vision is of a confident and capable sector, with the ability to raise funds from diverse sources. By increasing their long term sustainability, small charities can continue their vital role in helping to build a stronger society.</p><p> </p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch","4088","2017-07-17T13:43:01.673Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750089/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750089/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750089/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-07-10","Charities: Fund Raising","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what recent assessment she has made of the capacity of smaller charities to fundraise.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","4087"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750090","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-07-17","<p>Government is committed to building the resilience and independence of smaller charities. Through our ongoing dialogue with representatives from across the sector, we know that small charities can struggle to raise the resources they need.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>In recognition of this, the Office for Civil Society in England are providing a multi-year programme of fundraising training and support. In addition to face-to-face training, intensive one-to-one advice sessions and webinars, the programme includes skilled volunteer mentoring, connecting small charities with experienced fundraisers to provide longer term support. The training and support will be provided at little or no cost and the providers will also develop and share fundraising training resources and toolkits to support small charities who might not be able to attend training.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>Our vision is of a confident and capable sector, with the ability to raise funds from diverse sources. By increasing their long term sustainability, small charities can continue their vital role in helping to build a stronger society.</p><p> </p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch","4087","2017-07-17T13:43:01.767Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750090/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750090/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750090/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-07-10","Charities: Fund Raising","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what steps she is taking to support fundraising mentoring in the charitable sector.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","4088"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750091","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-09-19","<p>The information requested is not held centrally and to obtain it would incur a disproportionate cost.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock","3985 ; 4015","2017-09-19T13:43:05.34Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750091/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750091/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750091/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-07-10","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, how many contracts put out to tender by her Department have been (a) cancelled and (b) re-tendered in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","4000"
