"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750094","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-07-17","<p>The Ministry of Defence awards thousands of contracts a year. Information about these is published in the Trade Industry &amp; Contracts Statistical Bulletin which is available at the following link: https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/mod-trade-industry-and-contracts-2016</p><p>Information on whether these contracts are awarded through framework contracts is not held centrally and could be provided only at disproportionate cost. Similarly, tender and bid information is held with individual commercial teams and again could be provided only at disproportionate cost.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","3986 ; 4001","2017-07-17T13:58:07.993Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750094/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750094/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750094/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-07-10","Ministry of Defence: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what proportion of public procurement contracts his Department awarded through framework agreements in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","4016"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750095","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-07-17","<p>The Ministry of Defence awards thousands of contracts a year. Information about these is published in the Trade Industry &amp; Contracts Statistical Bulletin which is available at the following link: https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/mod-trade-industry-and-contracts-2016</p><p>Information on whether these contracts are awarded through framework contracts is not held centrally and could be provided only at disproportionate cost. Similarly, tender and bid information is held with individual commercial teams and again could be provided only at disproportionate cost.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","3986 ; 4016","2017-07-17T13:58:08.203Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750095/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750095/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750095/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-07-10","Ministry of Defence: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many contracts put out to tender by his Department have been (a) cancelled and (b) re-tendered in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","4001"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750096","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-07-17","<p>The RAF provides close air support in the form of airstrikes on Daesh targets, which assist the Syrian Democratic Forces on the ground in taking the fight to Daesh in places such as Raqqah.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-07-17T13:59:42.593Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750096/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750096/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750096/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-07-10","Syria: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what forms of military support the UK has given to the Syrian Democratic Forces who are taking part in the ground assault against Daesh in Raqqa.","false","Biography information for Matthew Pennycook","Greenwich and Woolwich","Matthew Pennycook","3972"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750097","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-07-17","<p>Through the Coalition, we impress on all local partner forces in the fight against Daesh the importance of respect for the Law of Armed Conflict and International Humanitarian Law.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-07-17T14:02:18.687Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750097/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750097/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750097/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-07-10","Syria: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what steps the Government is taking to ensure that the activities of its military partners in the counter-Daesh offensive in Syria are consistent with international laws aimed at protecting civilians in armed conflicts.","false","Biography information for Matthew Pennycook","Greenwich and Woolwich","Matthew Pennycook","3973"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750098","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-07-18","<p>Operations to liberate Raqqah City have only just commenced. We are working with our Coalition partners to ensure that once liberated, the population will have inclusive and legitimate local governance that can both protect and represent them.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-07-18T15:38:17.983Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750098/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750098/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750098/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-07-10","Syria: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, which governing entity or entities the Government expects will take control of Raqqa after the removal of Daesh from that city; and what steps the Government is taking to prevent the creation of a political vacuum in that city.","false","Biography information for Matthew Pennycook","Greenwich and Woolwich","Matthew Pennycook","3974"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750099","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-07-18","<p>Following implementation of the Government's updated policy guidance on steel procurement, the Ministry of Defence has engaged with its prime defence contractors to ensure their support in adhering to the practices and guidelines set out in the policy.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2017-07-18T13:36:12.75Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750099/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750099/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750099/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-07-10","Iron and Steel: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what steps his Department is taking to ensure that its prime contractors adhere to the Government's procurement practices and guidelines set out for the procurement of UK steel.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kinnock","Aberavon","Stephen Kinnock","3946"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750100","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-07-17","<p>The Ministry of Defence awards thousands of contracts a year. Information about these is published in the Trade Industry &amp; Contracts Statistical Bulletin which is available at the following link: https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/mod-trade-industry-and-contracts-2016</p><p>Information on whether these contracts are awarded through framework contracts is not held centrally and could be provided only at disproportionate cost. Similarly, tender and bid information is held with individual commercial teams and again could be provided only at disproportionate cost.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","4001 ; 4016","2017-07-17T13:58:08.09Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750100/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750100/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750100/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-07-10","Ministry of Defence: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the average number of bids received for each contract put out to tender by his Department was in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","3986"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750101","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-07-13","<p>I commend the good work that cadet forces do in Northern Ireland and welcome invitations to visit its cadet establishments. I have no immediate plans to visit cadet detachments in Northern Ireland but I would be very happy to consider such visits in the future.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-07-13T15:32:15.867Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750101/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750101/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750101/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-07-10","Armed Forces: Cadets","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what plans he has to visit cadet detachments in Northern Ireland in the current calendar year.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","3896"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750102","Department for Education","false","2017-07-24","<p>As announced by the Parliamentary Under Secretary of State for the School System on 4 July we will not be pursuing universal breakfasts for primary school children and we will be retaining the existing provision for universal infant free school meals.</p><p> </p><p>We will however invest in a breakfast club programme as announced in the Childhood Obesity Plan in August 2016. This committed £10 million a year of the Soft Drinks Industry Levy to expand breakfast club provision in up to 1,600 schools. Further details of the programme will be announced in due course.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-07-24T15:26:39.627Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750102/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750102/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750102/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-07-10","Primary Education: Breakfast Clubs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what her policy is on offering free breakfasts for all primary school children.","false","Biography information for Kate Green","Stretford and Urmston","Kate Green","3745"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750103","Department for Education","false","2017-07-18","<p>We want all children, regardless of their background, to benefit from a high quality education that provides them with the knowledge they need to succeed in modern Britain.</p><p>We want to ensure that all teachers have appropriate support to help them deliver this knowledge rich curriculum. To date, the Secretary of State has not had discussions with cultural or scientific institutions about the fund. We will provide further details about the curriculum fund in due course.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-07-18T08:12:24.84Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750103/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750103/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750103/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-07-10","Curriculum","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what discussions she has had with (a) cultural and (b) scientific institutions on the introduction of a new curriculum fund.","false","Biography information for Layla Moran","Oxford West and Abingdon","Layla Moran","3775"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750104","Department for Education","false","2017-07-14","<p>The department does not set pay and conditions for the early years workforce, which is predominantly made up of private and voluntary sector businesses. However, the mean average salary of full-time nursery nurses employed in all state funded schools in each of the past 5 years is provided in the following table. The source of this information is the School Workforce Census which is an annual survey collected in November each year. Salaries are rounded to the nearest £100.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Mean Salary</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>£19,300</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>£19,900</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>£20,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>£20,300</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>£20,500</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-07-14T10:46:06.723Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750104/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750104/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750104/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-07-10","Nursery Nurses: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what information her Department holds on the average wage paid to nursery nurses in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","3757"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750105","Department for Education","false","2017-07-14","<p>Based on the 2016 Survey of Childcare and Early Years Providers in England, we estimate that, excluding head teachers, senior managers and early years co-ordinators, 77% of group-based staff, 73% of nursery staff and 69% of reception staff were qualified to at least level 3. Again excluding head teachers, senior managers and early years co-ordinators, 7% of group based staff, 15% of nursery staff and 26% of reception staff were qualified to at least level 6. These figures include teaching staff, nursery nurses and other staff involved in the delivery of childcare and early years provision.’ The Survey is available online at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/childcare-and-early-years-providers-survey-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/childcare-and-early-years-providers-survey-2016</a>.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-07-14T10:42:50.663Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750105/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750105/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750105/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-07-10","Nursery Nurses: Qualifications","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what qualifications are held by nursery nurses at each employment level.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","3758"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750106","Department for Education","false","2017-07-14","<p>The department works closely with our national delivery contractor, Childcare Works, in supporting all local authorities (LA) to ensure they are ready to deliver from September 2017. LAs who have specific needs are offered targeted support packages. Each LA has a dedicated programme adviser assigned by Childcare Works to support them in their preparations for delivery.</p><p> </p><p>We are making record investments in the government’s free childcare offer: over £1 billion more per year by 2020. This includes £300 million per year for a significant increase to the hourly rates paid for two, three and four-year-old entitlement. From April 2017, the national average funding rates also increased to £4.94 for three and four-year-olds and £5.39 for two-year-olds. We are also investing £100m in capital funding to create nearly 18,000 additional places for eligible children to help meet demand from hardworking parents. This investment will support even more providers to deliver 30 hours.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-07-14T10:38:28.357Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750106/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750106/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750106/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-07-10","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many local authorities have made representation to her Department on their ability to deliver 30 hours free childcare to all applicable children from September 2017.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","3759"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750107","Department for Education","false","2017-07-14","<p>The department’s revised Early Education and Childcare Statutory Guidance for Local Authorities provides clear guidance to local authorities and providers in delivering the existing free entitlements for two, three and four-year-olds and the 30 hours extended entitlement.</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/596460/early_education_and_childcare_statutory_guidance_2017.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/596460/early_education_and_childcare_statutory_guidance_2017.pdf</a>.</p><p>The guidance clearly sets out that providers can charge parents for meals, consumables (such as nappies and sun cream) and for additional activities (such as trips and yoga), as long as parents are not required to pay any fee as a condition of taking up their child’s free entitlement place. In April, the department also published Operational Guidance, providing practical examples and case studies of how the free entitlements can be delivered, including examples of charging models.</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/610170/Operational_guidance.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/610170/Operational_guidance.pdf</a>.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-07-14T11:30:30.877Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750107/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750107/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750107/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-07-10","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what guidance her Department has given to nurseries and childcare providers on charging for (a) meals, (b) activities, (c) nappies and (d) any other items outwith the 30 free hours of childcare provided from September 2017.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","3760"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750108","Department for Education","false","2017-07-19","<p>The student funding system is fair and progressive. It removes financial barriers for anyone hoping to study and is backed by the taxpayer, with outstanding debt written off after 30 years. Monthly student loan repayments are linked to income, not to interest rates or the amount borrowed. Borrowers earning less than the repayment threshold (£21,000) repay nothing at all.</p><p> </p><p>Once borrowers leave study, those earning less than £21,000 are charged an interest rate of RPI only. Post-study interest rates are variable based on income, tapering up from RPI for those earning less than £21,000 to RPI+3% for borrowers earning £41,000 and above. The system of variable interest rates based on income makes the system more progressive, as higher earners contribute more to the sustainability of the higher education system.</p><p> </p><p>We have a world class student finance system that is working well, and that has led to record numbers of disadvantaged students benefiting from higher education. As ever, we will keep the detailed features of the system under review to ensure it remains fair and effective.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-07-19T15:42:39.197Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750108/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750108/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750108/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-07-10","Students: Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if she will consider setting a lower interest rate for student loans.","false","Biography information for Stephen Hammond","Wimbledon","Stephen Hammond","3771"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750109","Department for Education","false","2017-07-13","<p>Budgets for 16 to 19-year-old education are set on the basis of the established 16 to 19 funding rates and formula, using estimates of student numbers. In 2014-15 and 2015-16 student numbers and associated costs were lower than these estimates, which resulted in lower spending than the forecast, by £135m and £132m respectively, representing 2.2% of the budget. This was available for reallocation. Because this resulted from student numbers which were slightly lower than forecast, it did not affect funding per student. Final expenditure is not yet available for 2016-17 and will be published in Education and Skills Funding Agency accounts in due course.</p><p> </p>","Guildford","Anne Milton",,"2017-07-13T15:10:44.457Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750109/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750109/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750109/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-07-10","Sixth Form Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how much of her Department's budget allocated to 16 to 19-year old education was reallocated to other budgets in the financial years (a) 2014-15, (b) 2015-16 and (c) 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","3811"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750110","Department for Education","false","2017-07-14","<p>In March, we published a consultation document, ‘Primary Assessment in England’, which set out a number of proposals to improve the primary assessment system. One of those proposals was that a new assessment should be introduced in the reception year, to provide a new baseline for measuring the progress that pupils make at primary school. One of the potential benefits of introducing such an assessment would be that schools could receive greater credit for the education that they provide during reception, Year 1 and Year 2.</p><p>We made it clear that, once this new baseline assessment had become established, and its data available to calculate progress measures for pupils reaching the end of Key Stage 2, we would no longer require data from statutory assessments currently administered at the end of Key Stage 1.</p><p>We sought views on whether those Key Stage 1 assessments should be made non-statutory.</p><p>The consultation exercise closed on 22 June, and we will be publishing our response in due course. The consultation document is available to read at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/primary-assessment-in-england" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/consultations/primary-assessment-in-england</a>.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-07-14T13:45:35.413Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750110/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750110/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750110/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-07-10","Primary Education: Assessments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what progress she has made on her plans to abolish SATs at Key Stage 1; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Stephen McPartland","Stevenage","Stephen McPartland","3891"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750111","Department for Education","false","2017-07-18","<p>The Government recently published data from the Longitudinal Education Outcomes (LEO) dataset on graduate earnings up to 5 years after graduation. The data are available for each university split by degree subject studied and can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/graduate-outcomes-for-all-subjects-by-university" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/graduate-outcomes-for-all-subjects-by-university</a>.</p><p> </p><p>Average earnings were not published for each institution as a whole as the overall earnings for an institution would be strongly influenced by the subject mix offered.</p><p> </p><p>The Higher Education Statistics Agency (HESA) have published an estimate of earnings based on a survey of graduates three and a half years after graduation. The median salary of Russell Group leavers was £29,500. The data can be found here:</p><p><a href="https://www.hesa.ac.uk/data-and-analysis/publications/long-destinations-2010-11" target="_blank">https://www.hesa.ac.uk/data-and-analysis/publications/long-destinations-2010-11</a>.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-07-18T14:38:10.777Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750111/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750111/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750111/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-07-10","Graduates: Average Earnings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what information her Department holds on the average salary for a graduate from a Russell group university.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","4107"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750112","Department for Education","false","2017-07-18","<p>The 2016 UKCES Working Futures publication estimates that 14.9 million jobs will become vacant between 2014 and 2024, and nearly half of these (47 per cent) will be in the occupations most likely to employ graduates (SOC 1-3; Managers, professionals and associate professionals).</p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-07-18T14:33:48.587Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750112/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750112/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750112/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-07-10","Graduates: Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what estimate she has made of the proportion of jobs in the UK economy that will require a degree level education in the next 10 years.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","4109"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750113","Department for Education","false","2017-07-18","<p>There is no programme called “teach second”; therefore, we are unable to provide any data.</p><p>Teach First do however recruit career changers and young professionals into teaching. This group made up 27% of the 2016 cohort of trainees.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-07-18T08:11:01.593Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750113/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750113/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750113/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-07-10","Teachers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many teach second teachers there are in (a) England, (b) the South East and (c) Southampton.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","4126"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750114","Department for Education","false","2017-07-18","<p>The Government regularly publishes information on graduate employment trends through its ‘Graduate Labour Market Statistics’ publication, which can be found on the gov.uk website; <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/graduate-labour-market-quarterly-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/graduate-labour-market-quarterly-statistics</a>.</p><p>According to the most recent publication, in 2016 the median salary for graduates was £32,000. This compares to a median salary of £22,500 for non-graduates.</p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-07-18T14:35:36.263Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750114/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750114/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750114/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-07-10","Graduates: Average Earnings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what information her Department holds on the average salary for a university graduate; and what that figure is for people who did not attend university.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","4108"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750115","Department for Education","false","2017-07-18","<p>The table in the attachment shows the number and percentage of pupils currently in good or outstanding schools in schools by previous Ofsted judgement.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-07-18T16:35:05.877Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750115/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750115/answer","4123 attachment.xlsx","4123 attachment.xlsx","% currently in good or outstanding schools","% currently in good or outstanding schools","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750115/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-07-10","Schools: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many children were in good or outstanding schools in (a) England, (b) the South East and (c) Southampton in each of the last seven years for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","4123"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750116","Department for Education","false","2017-07-18","<p>In November 2016, the latest information available, there were an estimated 130,600 teachers teaching STEM subjects in state funded secondary schools in England. This represents 58% of all secondary school teachers.</p><p>The numbers of teachers teaching each subject in secondary schools are estimated using data provided by secondary schools to the annual School Workforce Census. Typically, the census receives data for over 70% of secondary school teachers. This sample data is then weighted and grossed up so that nationally representative figures can be produced. Due to the sample nature of the data received, regional and local estimates are not produced.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-07-18T08:08:40.597Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750116/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750116/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750116/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-07-10","Teachers: STEM Subjects","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many STEM teachers there are in (a) England, (b) the South East and (c) Southampton.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","4124"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750117","Department for Education","false","2017-07-18","<p>Teach First have advised there are currently the following numbers of Teach First teachers in England, the South East and Southampton:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Number of Teach First teachers</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>England</p></td><td><p>5716</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>South East</p></td><td><p>432</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Southampton</p></td><td><p>32</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-07-18T08:09:44.01Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750117/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750117/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750117/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-07-10","Teachers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many teach first teachers there are in (a) England, (b) the South East and (c) Southampton.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","4125"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750118","Department for Education","false","2017-07-18","<p>Officials from the Department have met with head teachers from across the country to discuss school funding, as part of our consultation on a schools and high needs national formulae.</p><p> </p><p>We received over 25,000 responses to the consultation. We are grateful to all those who expressed their views on school funding and the proposed formula as part of this process. We will publish the response to the consultation in due course.</p><p> </p><p>The core schools budget has been protected in real terms since 2010 and will be £41bn in 2017-18. We recognise, nevertheless, that schools are facing cost pressures and we will continue to provide support to help them use their funding in cost effective ways. This includes tools, information and guidance to support improved financial health and efficiency in schools, including School Workforce Planning Guidance to help schools make well-informed decisions about their staff structures. These can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/schools-financial-health-and-efficiency" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/schools-financial-health-and-efficiency</a>.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","3917","2017-07-18T08:37:27.167Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750118/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750118/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750118/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-07-10","Schools: North East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what recent discussions she has had with headteachers in (a) Jarrow constituency, (b) South Tyneside local authority area and (c) Gateshead local authority area on (i) school funding and (ii) the effect of the new school funding formula on schools in those areas.","false","Biography information for Mr Stephen Hepburn","Jarrow","Mr Stephen Hepburn","3919"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750119","Department for Education","false","2017-07-18","<p>Officials from the Department have met with head teachers from across the country to discuss school funding, as part of our consultation on a schools and high needs national formulae.</p><p> </p><p>We received over 25,000 responses to the consultation. We are grateful to all those who expressed their views on school funding and the proposed formula as part of this process. We will publish the response to the consultation in due course.</p><p> </p><p>The core schools budget has been protected in real terms since 2010 and will be £41bn in 2017-18. We recognise, nevertheless, that schools are facing cost pressures and we will continue to provide support to help them use their funding in cost effective ways. This includes tools, information and guidance to support improved financial health and efficiency in schools, including School Workforce Planning Guidance to help schools make well-informed decisions about their staff structures. These can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/schools-financial-health-and-efficiency" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/schools-financial-health-and-efficiency</a>.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","3919","2017-07-18T08:37:27.277Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750119/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750119/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750119/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-07-10","Teachers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment she has made of the potential effect of the proposed school funding formula on the number of teaching posts in (a) Jarrow constituency, (b) South Tyneside, (c) the North East and (d) the UK.","false","Biography information for Mr Stephen Hepburn","Jarrow","Mr Stephen Hepburn","3917"
