"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750341","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-07-18","<p><strong> </strong></p><p>Calls to 0345 numbers incur geographic costing tariffs, so like ‘01’ and ‘02’ numbers are often included within inclusive and free caller packages.</p><p> </p><p>Callers whose network provider does not offer these schemes are generally charged at 9p per minute and from mobile phones cost between 3p and 55p to 0345 numbers.</p><p>Therefore the cost of a call duration of 00:07:30 (h:m:s) could range between 0.23p - £4.13.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-07-18T14:47:46.907Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750341/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750341/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750341/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-10","Department for Work and Pensions: Telephone Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate he has made of the cost to claimants of an average length call to his Department's 0345 numbers.","false","Biography information for Margaret Greenwood","Wirral West","Margaret Greenwood","4086"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750342","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-07-18","<p>I refer the Honourable Member for Stretford and Urmston to the answer given by the Right Honourable member for Ashford in response to PQ3079.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-07-18T14:36:55.82Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750342/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750342/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750342/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-10","Department for Work and Pensions: Equality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to the oral Answer of 2 November 2016, Official Report, column 879, what steps his Department has taken to use 2011 census classifications, including on Gypsies and Travellers, to audit racial disparities in public service outcomes.","false","Biography information for Kate Green","Stretford and Urmston","Kate Green","4064"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750343","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-07-17","<p>The latest available data on personal independence payment (PIP) clearances split by parliamentary constituency and by type of clearance (i.e. whether the claim was awarded, disallowed or withdrawn) for both new claims and reassessed claims, can be found at <a href="https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/</a></p><p> </p><p>Guidance on how to use Stat-Xplore can be found here:</p><p><a href="https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/index.html" target="_blank">https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/index.html</a>.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-07-17T11:00:31.587Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750343/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750343/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750343/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-10","Disability Living Allowance: Vale of Clwyd","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many and what proportion of constituents in Vale of Clwyd constituency in receipt of disability living allowance have subsequently been assessed as ineligible for personal independence payments in each year for which data is available.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","4074"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750344","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-07-17","<p>As of December 2016 there were 390 (to the nearest 10) people in receipt of Universal Credit in the Southampton and Itchen constituency.</p><p> </p><p>This information is published and available at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk" target="_blank">https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk</a></p><p> </p><p>Guidance for users is available at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Getting-Started.html" target="_blank">https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Getting-Started.html</a></p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-07-17T14:46:52.06Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750344/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750344/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750344/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-10","Universal Credit: Southampton","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people are in receipt of universal credit in Southampton.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","4110"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750345","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-07-17","<p>We have a number of safeguards in place to help claimants transition to Universal Credit including Advances and Budgeting Support. Claimants can apply for an advance immediately and can receive up to 50 percent of their indicative award shortly afterwards. Personal Budgeting Support is also discussed at the claimant’s initial work search interview to gauge their potential support needs and can include money advice. We continue to work closely with landlords, Local Authorities and other organisations to ensure claimants are supported throughout the assessment process.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-07-17T14:51:26.303Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750345/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750345/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750345/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-10","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what support is given to claimants of universal credit during the assessment process.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","4112"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750346","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-07-18","<p>I have interpreted your question to refer to Universal Credit Hardship Payments, which are made on the understanding that they are recoverable from the customer. Repayment support is available in several ways when a hardship payment is made.</p><p> </p><p>Recovery of a Universal Credit Recoverable Hardship Payment can only start when the claimant’s award is not subject to a sanction or fraud penalty reduction.</p><p> </p><p>There are established processes to consider hardship if the proposed rate of repayment cannot be afforded. The claimant will be asked to provide evidence to support their position, for example, bank statements, and details of their income and expenditure. Their financial circumstances can then be taken into account and a possible reduction in repayment considered. Suspension of repayment may also be considered under certain circumstances such as unexpected extra expenditure.</p><p> </p><p>As a means to support claimants into work, recovery of a Hardship Payment is suspended for any Assessment Period where the claimant’s earnings at least equal their individual Conditionality Earnings Threshold.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-07-18T14:34:21.797Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750346/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750346/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750346/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-10","Means-tested Benefits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what repayment support is given to claimants who take out a hardship payment.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","4113"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750347","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-07-17","<p>Universal Credit is still in its implementation phase. However evidence shows that it is effective in reducing worklessness.</p><p> </p><p>In Universal Credit more people are finding work than under Jobseeker’s Allowance. They are spending more time looking for work and moving into work faster. Additionally, in Universal Credit more people are actively looking to increase their earnings whilst they are in work.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-07-17T15:09:08.047Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750347/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750347/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750347/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-10","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what review of the universal credit policy has been undertaken since its implementation; and what assessment that review made of the effectiveness of that policy at reducing the number of workless households.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","4111"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750348","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-07-17","<p>Any individual experiencing financial hardship while awaiting payment of their benefit award can apply for a Short Term Benefit Advance (STBA). The award of an STBA is based upon eligibility criteria. Payments of a STBA are recovered from benefit once it has been awarded.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-07-17T11:00:06.48Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750348/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750348/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750348/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-10","Social Security Benefits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what income support is given to benefit claimants who transition from one benefit to another to prevent long periods of no income.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","4115"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750349","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-07-17","<p>The information requested is not readily available and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-07-17T15:18:58.723Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750349/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750349/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750349/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-10","Means-tested Benefits: Southampton","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many claimants in Southampton have taken out a hardship payment.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","4114"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750350","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-07-18","<p>The Department for Work and Pensions e-procurement system does not hold accurate data on cancelled or retendered contracts.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-07-18T14:58:44.43Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750350/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750350/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750350/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-10","Department for Work and Pensions: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many contracts put out to tender by his Department have been (a) cancelled and (b) re-tendered in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","4011"
